Generally, public policies will have *winners and losers*: in theory, if the net benefit is positive, we could reward the losers &mdash; this is the idea behind the **Kaldor-Hicks criterion**:  a policy is desirable if winners could *hypothetically* reward losers, and the cost-benefit analysis finds such efficient policies
